n average, the codebase grows faster than it can be verified (265 untested INVs), documented (142 spec-impl gaps), or tracked (hypothesis degrading). SOLUTION: (1) Prune open issues aggressively — close anything not on the critical path for S0 validation. (2) Freeze issue creation during verification sprint. (3) Consider whether the beads issue tracker + braid task store dual-tracking adds overhead without proportional value. VERIFICATION: Open issue count below 30. Zero issues in phases beyond current phase gate. DEPENDENCIES: Independent administrative action.; AUDIT-LOOP-3: Learning Loop 3 (Ontology Discovery/OBSERVER-6) partially closed -- shallow feedback only. Observation: LIVE -- braid observe embeds each observation, assign_to_concepts_soft() matches against concepts. At harvest, crystallize_concepts() runs agglomerative clustering. Analysis: LIVE -- O(n^2) clustering, TF-IDF names, variance computation, split/merge detection. Feedback: SHALLOW -- concepts feed routing via concept_dampening() (routing.rs:906) which deprioritizes well-observed areas. But concepts do NOT: (1) create new schema attributes (no ontology categories). (2) propose new boundary definitions (no structural feedback). (3) modify ISP classification. (4) feed into hypothesis ledger. Also: DOGFOOD-2 scored 3.48/10. The hash embedder produces deterministic but semantically poor embeddings -- this is a FIXABLE implementation issue (Model2Vec via embeddings feature flag exists and is implemented), not architectural. SOLUTION: (1) Enable Model2Vec embeddings by default (fix concept quality). (2) When concept variance stays below threshold for N sessions, propose new boundary connecting concept entities to existing boundaries. (3) Feed concept stability metrics into hypothesis ledger for calibration. VERIFICATION: After Model2Vec enabled, rerun DOGFOOD-2 scoring. Verify concept quality improves above 6/10. DEPENDENCIES: Quality fix (Model2Vec) is independent. Boundary proposal depends on AUDIT-C8-7 (dynamic boundaries).; AUDIT-TYPE-006: Store could benefit from initialization typestate tracking (Genesis/Bootstrapped/Ready). PROBLEM: Store goes through distinct lifecycle phases: genesis (no schema), bootstrapped (Layer 0), full-schema (Layers 0-4). All phases share the same type. Functions requiring full schema receive a bare Store with no compile-time guarantee. Confidence: 0.5 — this is a nice-to-have, not a correctness issue. SOLUTION: Consider Store<Genesis>/Store<Bootstrapped>/Store<Ready> typestate or a sealed marker trait. VERIFICATION: Functions requiring schema accept Store<Ready> only. DEPENDS-ON: W1-003 (schema layer changes affect lifecycle). INTERACTS-WITH: None.; META-4: Scope creep — Phase C/D features built before Phase B (S0-CLOSE) complete [STRATEGIC, from PROJECT_ASSESSMENT]. Sessions 044-046 added concept engine (198 KB), inquiry engine, online calibration (scored 4.1/10), and PERF-REGRESSION epic (16 tasks). These are Phase C/D (Intelligence, Self-Calibration) features. Meanwhile Phase B (Lifecycle) item S0-CLOSE remains open, hypothesis ledger is degrading, 265 INVs are untested, and F(S) hasnt moved in 13 sessions. The project is building intelligence on top of uncalibrated infrastructure. The concept engine work (Sessions 044-045) is particularly concerning: HashEmbedder was known bottleneck, online calibration scored 4.1/10, concept collapse persists — three sessions on a feature that doesnt work yet while the core calibration pipeline was left broken. SOLUTION: Enforce phase gating: no Phase C/D work until Phase B passes its quality gate (S0-CLOSE validated, F(S) above 0.70, hypothesis mean error below 0.30). This is the discipline fix — stop adding, start verifying. VERIFICATION: Track phase gate metrics. If F(S) drops or hypothesis error rises, automatically defer new-feature tasks. DEPENDENCIES: Related to META-1 (Type 9 self-diagnosis) — the system should enforce its own phase gates.; OPEN-LOOP-5: Concept bridge gaps displayed but not routed to guidance [from AUDIT_REPORT]. braid status shows bridge-gaps between concept clusters (e.g. concept-with-from/different-threshold-this). These represent knowledge areas that should be connected but arent. However, the bridge gap information is only displayed — it does not feed into the routing system as high-priority work items. A bridge gap represents an opportunity for the acquisition function: observations that connect two isolated concept clusters have high expected information gain. SOLUTION: Feed bridge gaps into routing as synthetic tasks with elevated alpha scores. When a bridge gap persists for N sessions, the guidance system should recommend observations that span the gap. VERIFICATION: After 3 sessions with persistent bridge gap, braid status next-action recommends bridging observation. DEPENDENCIES: Depends on AUDIT-LOOP-3 (concept quality — bridge gaps are meaningless if concepts are collapsed). Lower priority until Model2Vec enabled.; AUDIT-CORR-002: Datalog CALM compliance should reject non-monotonic queries at parse time, not silently return empty. PROBLEM: stratum.rs classify() returns S2 for Rule/Or/Frontier clauses, and check_stage0() rejects them. But the evaluator (evaluator.rs:95-119) prints eprintln warnings and returns vec![] for these clause types — silently returning empty results instead of an error. INV-QUERY-001 calls for parse-time rejection. SOLUTION: Evaluate stratum BEFORE execution. Return QueryError::NonMonotonicInStage0 for S2+ queries in Stage 0. The warning should be an error. VERIFICATION: (1) Query with Rule clause returns QueryError in Stage 0. (2) Query with only :find/:where clauses succeeds. DEPENDS-ON: None. INTERACTS-WITH: None.; AUDIT-SOUND-1: Coherence gate unwired from write path [CRITICAL]. The coherence gate (coherence.rs, 1300 LOC, 18 tests) is disconnected from the CLI write path. LiveStore::write_tx() at live_store.rs:183 calls store.apply_datoms() directly, bypassing both schema validation and coherence checking. The ONLY production caller of transact_with_coherence() is proposal.rs:468 (proposal acceptance). This means 99%+ of store mutations (braid observe, write assert, task create, harvest, spec create) have zero contradiction prevention. SOLUTION: Wire transact_with_coherence() into LiveStore::write_tx(). Replace store.apply_datoms(&tx.datoms) with store.transact_with_coherence(&tx, force=false). Approximately 20-line change. JUSTIFICATION: First principles -- the coherence gate is the primary contradiction prevention mechanism. Without it, the append-only store (C1) guarantees permanence of contradictions. VERIFICATION: (1) Integration test: write_path_rejects_contradiction() -- build contradicting tx, assert write_tx returns Err. (2) E2E: braid write assert conflicting values, verify rejection. (3) Regression: all existing tests must still pass. DEPENDENCIES: None (standalone, highest-priority). Blocks all loop closure work. ACCRETIVE VALUE: 90.0 (impact=0.9, effort=0.1, risk=0.1). Est: 0.5 sessions.; MINOR-2: LiveStore refresh has TOCTOU window [LOW, from FULL_AUDIT F-CONC-002]. refresh_if_needed() checks has_new_external_txns() via directory mtime, then reads new transaction files. Between check and read, another agent could write additional transactions that are missed. Classic TOCTOU. Mitigated: daemon holds store in memory; CLI refreshes before every command; content-addressed files are immutable so missed file caught on next refresh. Window is short (one command invocation). SOLUTION: Document as known behavior. No fix needed at current scale. At multi-agent scale, consider inotify-based watching or lockfile coordination. VERIFICATION: Documentation only. DEPENDENCIES: Will matter more when AUDIT-LOOP-2 (multi-agent coordination) is implemented.; CORR-1: LIVE view ignores bare retractions and hardcodes LWW for ALL attributes [CRITICAL, from FULL_AUDIT F-INV-001 + AUDIT_REPORT F-CORR-002]. Two related defects in store.rs index_datom(): (1) Retraction ordering: the LIVE view uses live_view.remove() which only works if retracted value matches current LIVE value. If retraction arrives before assertion (possible in CRDT merge), LIVE view wont reflect it when assertion later arrives. The from_datoms() rebuild processes in BTreeSet order (entity,attr,value,tx,op) not causal (tx) order, so assert-before-retract is not guaranteed. (2) LWW hardcoded: index_datom() at store.rs:1089-1100 applies last-writer-wins regardless of schema-declared resolution mode. Multi-cardinality attributes silently lose all but latest value. store.live_value() returns incorrect results for non-LWW attributes. INV-STORE-012 violated. SOLUTION: (1) LIVE rebuild must process datoms in causal (tx) order, not BTreeSet order. Incremental path must check retracted value matches current LIVE before removing. (2) Route LIVE view updates through schema.resolution_mode(attr) — Multi-cardinality keeps all values, Lattice applies join. VERIFICATION: Proptest with 10K random assert/retract sequences in random order, verify LIVE matches fold-based computation over causally-sorted datoms. Unit test for Multi-cardinality attribute retaining multiple values. DEPENDENCIES: Blocks correct F(S) computation (bilateral reads LIVE). Blocks AUDIT-SOUND-1 (coherence gate should check against correct LIVE state). Interacts with AUDIT-PERF-2 (merge rebuild should use corrected LIVE logic).; AUDIT-EXT TYPE-9 (from PROJECT_ASSESSMENT Section 8): The deepest question — is the system observing its own failure to converge? PROBLEM: The project's bedrock claim is that it implements observe-compare-reduce at every level. But the system's most important discrepancy — F(S) stagnant at 0.62 for 13 sessions, hypothesis ledger degrading, 265 untested INVs accumulating — is not being detected, diagnosed, or reduced by the system itself. A human reading the dashboard sees these numbers. But: does the guidance system emit 'your verification pipeline is the bottleneck'? Does the routing function prioritize verification tasks over new feature tasks when the spec-impl gap is widening? Does the harvest capture 'F(S) hasn't moved in 5 sessions — this is anomalous'? JUSTIFICATION: If Braid is truly a learning system, it should detect its own stagnation as Type 9 divergence (Reflexive: system vs system's-model-of-itself) and recommend the verification sprint that the external assessment recommends. If it can't — if it takes an external audit to identify the obvious — then the self-improvement loop (the Y-combinator property from session-038) isn't yet operational. The test: run 'braid status' and 'braid seed --task improve convergence' and see if the system recommends what this assessment recommends. SOLUTION: This is not a code fix — it is a fitness function enhancement. F(S) stagnation over N sessions should trigger an anomaly detection signal. The guidance routing should detect when the spec-impl gap is widening and prioritize verification over new features. VERIFICATION: braid seed --task 'improve convergence' recommends verification sprint without human intervention. DEPENDENCIES: Requires calibration fix, coverage bug fix, and verification sprint to validate. This is the meta-level test of whether the system works. FINDING SOURCE: PROJECT_ASSESSMENT.md Section 8. SEVERITY: Critical (existential).; AUDIT-EXT CONVERGENCE-DIAGNOSIS (from PROJECT_ASSESSMENT Section 4): F(S) stagnant at 0.62 for 13 sessions — specification denominator growth outpacing verification numerator growth. PROBLEM: F(S) has been at 0.62 +/- 0.02 for Sessions 033-046 (13 sessions). The saw-tooth model predicts oscillation but we see flatness. The three F(S) components most sensitive to the verification gap: V (Validation, weight 0.18) — 265 untested INVs score V=0, C (Coverage, weight 0.18) — 142 spec entities lack impl links, I (Incompleteness, weight 0.08) — unfalsifiable specs score 0.15 instead of 0. Quantitative estimate: if all 265 untested INVs were verified to L2+ witness, F(S) would rise to approximately 0.72-0.78. JUSTIFICATION: This is the central convergence diagnosis. The project has expanded its specification horizon (new INVs, new learning loops, new engines) faster than it verifies what exists. Every session adds ~10 specs and ~10 verifications, keeping the ratio constant. To break this equilibrium and observe the saw-tooth, the project needs a verification-only sprint (3-5 sessions with no new specs). If F(S) rises to ~0.78 after the sprint, the convergence model is validated. If it doesn't, something deeper is wrong — and that's worth knowing. SOLUTION: Freeze all new specification and feature work. Verify the 265 untested INVs. Target F(S) >= 0.78. VERIFICATION: F(S) rises from 0.62 to >= 0.75 after verification sprint. DEPENDENCIES: Requires F-ERR-003 (clippy green) and AUDIT-EXT-CRITICAL-1 (coherence gate) first. FINDING SOURCE: PROJECT_ASSESSMENT.md Section 4. FILES: All spec/ and test files. SEVERITY: High (strategic). WAVE: 3. EFFORT: 40h (5 sessions).; CORR-3: Index synchronization depends on programmer discipline — 3 divergent insertion paths [HIGH, from FULL_AUDIT F-INV-003]. Five secondary indexes + MaterializedViews are maintained by index_datom() in store.rs, but there is no compile-time enforcement that this call happens for every datom insertion. Four insertion paths exist: (1) genesis() calls views.observe_datom() but NOT index_datom() — indexes rebuilt in from_datoms(). (2) from_datoms() calls views.observe_datom() then rebuilds indexes separately. (3) apply_tx() calls index_datom() per datom — the correct path. (4) apply_datoms() rebuilds everything from scratch. Paths 1 and 2 use observe_datom() directly, bypassing index_datom(). MaterializedViews and index paths are not unified. SOLUTION: Make index_datom() the sole function that updates BOTH indexes AND MaterializedViews. Remove the separate observe_datom() method. All paths (genesis, from_datoms, apply_tx, apply_datoms) call index_datom. VERIFICATION: grep -n observe_datom store.rs returns only definition and calls from index_datom. All existing tests pass. DEPENDENCIES: Prerequisite for CORR-1 (LIVE view fix) — unified path ensures LIVE correction applies everywhere. Interacts with AUDIT-PERF-2 (merge rebuild uses apply_datoms path).; AUDIT-LOOP-1: Learning Loop 1 (Calibration/OBSERVER-4) partially closed -- last-mile problem. Observation: LIVE -- hypotheses recorded at harvest (routing.rs:1198). Analysis: LIVE -- outcomes matched at task close (task.rs:1176), calibration metrics computed (routing.rs:1355). Feedback: COMPUTED BUT NOT TRANSACTED. policy.rs:394 calibrate_boundary_weights() correctly computes weight adjustments with 0.1 learning rate, threshold gating, normalization. policy.rs:554 apply_weight_adjustments() generates the datoms. But apply_weight_adjustments is NEVER CALLED from the CLI. braid status displays recommendations but does not transact them. SOLUTION: Call apply_weight_adjustments() from braid harvest --commit. The harvest command is the natural point for calibration feedback since it already produces hypotheses. After fixing AUDIT-SOUND-3 (dimensional mismatch), this closes Loop 1 completely. JUSTIFICATION: NEG-010 -- every piece of information must feed back into coherence model. Weight adjustments are computed but not applied = open loop. VERIFICATION: Record 10 hypotheses, close 5 tasks, run harvest --commit. Verify policy weights change. Verify F(S) boundary scores reflect updated weights. DEPENDENCIES: Depends on AUDIT-SOUND-3 (dimensional mismatch must be fixed first or calibration feeds back noise). Also needs AUDIT-SOUND-1 (coherence gate) so feedback datoms are validated.; C8-EXT-2: Guidance system (14137 LOC) is deeply DDIS-specific — largest C8 violation by LOC [HIGH, from FULL_AUDIT F-C8-004 + AUDIT_REPORT]. guidance.rs + methodology.rs + routing.rs + context.rs = 14137 LOC (17% of kernel). Contains: classify_command() hardcoding braid CLI commands, basin competition model (Basin A = DDIS, Basin B = pretrained patterns), COTX routing rules for finding/task/ADR/question categories, default derivation rules referencing invariant and adr artifact types, M(t) methodology score with DDIS-specific telemetry. The guidance FRAMEWORK (budget-aware projection, context blocks, routing) is substrate-agnostic. The guidance CONTENT (basin model, COTX rules, command classification) is DDIS-specific. These are entangled in the same module. SOLUTION: Extract DDIS guidance to plugin. Kernel provides GuidanceProvider trait; DDIS plugin implements it. Policy datoms specify which provider to use. Kernel guidance module retains only framework infrastructure. VERIFICATION: Kernel guidance module contains no string literal referencing invariant, ADR, harvest, or bilateral. DDIS logic in separate module/crate. DEPENDENCIES: Largest C8 task (~40 hours). Independent of schema migration but benefits from it. Should be Wave 2 work.; AUDIT-COH-1: Five namespaces critically undertested -- SYNC 0%, COHERENCE 8%, INTERFACE 20%, SIGNAL 17%, REFLEXIVE 20%. Combined: 34 untested invariants. SYNC (0/5 tested): multi-agent coordination safety completely unverified. COHERENCE (1/13 tested): density matrix axioms, spectral coherence, all theoretical foundations unverified. Only INV-COHERENCE-001 has any code. INTERFACE (2/10 tested): MCP tool descriptions, error recovery, CLI/MCP equivalence all unverified. SIGNAL (1/6 tested): only confusion re-association tested; signal-as-datom, subscription, severity routing, taxonomy completeness untested. REFLEXIVE (1/5 tested): ninth divergence type barely explored. Additionally TOPOLOGY at 38% (6/16 tested) and LAYOUT at 64% (7/11) have significant gaps. Total verification debt: 73 untested invariants across 20 namespaces. SOLUTION: Prioritize by risk: SYNC and COHERENCE first (foundational for multi-agent coordination). Then SIGNAL (foundational for divergence routing). INTERFACE and REFLEXIVE can be deferred. VERIFICATION: Create test suites for each namespace, track coverage monotonically. DEPENDENCIES: SYNC testing requires AUDIT-LOOP-2 (temporal coupling) for full coverage. COHERENCE testing requires AUDIT-SOUND-2 (F(S) semantics) to be settled.; META-2: Specification denominator growth outpacing verification numerator — root cause of F(S) stagnation [STRATEGIC, from PROJECT_ASSESSMENT convergence diagnosis]. F(S) = 0.62 for 13 sessions (033-046). Diagnosis: spec growth consistently outpaces verification, creating pseudo-steady state. Each session adds ~10 specs and ~10 verifications, keeping ratio constant. V (validation, weight 0.18): 265 untested INVs score V=0 for those elements. C (coverage, weight 0.18): 142 spec entities lack impl link. As new specs added, C drops unless implementations follow immediately. Quantitative estimate: if all 265 untested INVs verified to L2+, F(S) would rise to approximately 0.72-0.78. The saw-tooth model predicts oscillation (surprise then consolidation) but we see flatness — the recovery phase never happens because the project keeps adding specs (surprise) without consolidating (verification). SOLUTION: Verification-only sprint of 3-5 sessions. Zero new features or specs. For each untested INV, add L2+ witness test. This empirically tests whether F(S) can move. If it rises to 0.75+, convergence model validated. If not, F(S) formulation has a structural ceiling and needs revision. VERIFICATION: F(S) change after sprint. Target: delta-F(S) of at least +0.10. DEPENDENCIES: Depends on CORR-1 (LIVE view fix) for accurate F(S). Depends on AUDIT-COH-4 (F(S) path unification) for consistent measurement. This is the empirical test of the entire project thesis.; AUDIT-EXT OPEN-LOOPS (from AUDIT_REPORT Phase 1 Q6): 7 additional open loops beyond those in FULL_AUDIT loop analysis. (1) Signal datoms (:signal/*) stored but never read by any boundary — F(S) or M(t) should include signal coverage. (2) Exploration confidence set once at creation, never updated — calibration should update from outcomes. (3) Bootstrap hypotheses module never called from CLI — dead code that should feed hypothesis ledger. (4) Proposal lifecycle stored as datoms — no F(S) credit for accepted proposals. (5) Individual divergence detections returned to caller and printed to stderr — should be stored as datoms. (6) Concept bridge gaps displayed in status — no guidance routing for bridge-gap closure. (7) Witness challenge verdicts stored and update depth — no feedback to challenge parameters (difficulty, frequency). JUSTIFICATION: NEG-010 (Do Not Open Loops) is the strongest negative case in the system. Each open loop represents data produced without consumption by a boundary evaluation. Together with the 3 open + 2 broken + 2 phantom loops from FULL_AUDIT, this totals 14 open/broken/phantom loops — a significant learning-loop debt. SOLUTION: Each loop needs specific wiring: signal→boundary, confidence→calibration, proposals→F(S) credit, detections→datoms, bridges→guidance, verdicts→parameters. VERIFICATION: Each data flow terminates in a boundary evaluation or documented residual. DEPENDENCIES: These are Phase 2-3 work items. The calibration loop (loops 2,3) is highest priority. FILES: signal.rs, concept.rs, bootstrap_hypotheses.rs, proposal.rs, witness.rs. SEVERITY: Medium (individually), High (collectively). WAVE: 5. EFFORT: 30h total.; AUDIT-PERF-2: merge() rebuilds ALL indexes from scratch even for 0 new datoms. store.rs:1452-1565 merge() implementation: after set union of datom sets, clears all 5 indexes + MaterializedViews + schema, then iterates ALL datoms in merged store. For 108K datoms, this is O(108K * 5 index insertions) even for idempotent self-merge. SOLUTION: Incremental delta merge strategy: (1) Compute delta = other.datoms - self.datoms (new datoms only). (2) For each new datom, insert into indexes and MaterializedViews incrementally. (3) Skip if delta is empty. Complexity: O(M log N) where M = new datoms instead of O((N+M) log(N+M)). JUSTIFICATION: merge() is functionally sound (Kani-proven idempotency) but the full rebuild is a performance cliff that scales linearly with store size. VERIFICATION: Benchmark: merge empty store, verify O(1). Merge 100 new datoms into 100K store, verify linear in 100 not 100K. Proptest: verify incremental merge produces identical result to full rebuild. DEPENDENCIES: Related to AUDIT-PERF-1 (scans) but independent implementation.; AUDIT-COH-5: Signal system is an open loop -- datoms produced but no subscription dispatch. Signal system (signal.rs) detects 8 divergence types (confusion, logical, procedural, temporal, consequential, aleatory, axiological, epistemic) and produces signal datoms. But there is no subscription mechanism to ROUTE signals to appropriate resolution handlers. Signals are created and stored but never acted upon automatically. INV-SIGNAL-002 (confusion triggers re-association) is the only tested signal behavior. SOLUTION: Implement signal subscription dispatch (referenced as SIGNAL-002 in spec). Each signal type maps to a resolution handler: confusion -> re-ASSOCIATE, logical -> contradiction detection, procedural -> dynamic CLAUDE.md update, etc. When a signal is created, dispatch to registered handlers. VERIFICATION: Create each signal type, verify the corresponding handler fires. E2E: produce a confusion signal, verify seed output includes refreshed association. DEPENDENCIES: Independent but interacts with AUDIT-LOOP-2 (temporal coupling could be a signal source).; AUDIT-C8-6: Cargo/Rust build commands hardcoded in kernel [HARD C8 violation, Priority 6]. topology.rs:797 hardcodes: Do NOT run cargo fmt, cargo clippy, or cargo test. seed.rs:2770-2771 hardcodes: Quality: cargo check && cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings && cargo fmt --check && cargo test. These Rust-specific tool names should come from policy or CLI layer. A Go project needs go fmt, go vet, go test. SOLUTION: For topology.rs: reference a policy-defined verification command rather than hardcoding Cargo. For seed.rs: the cargo commands are gated by is_braid check (partial mitigation) but should still come from policy. Move verification command definitions to CLI layer or policy manifest. VERIFICATION: Configure Go quality gates in policy, verify seed output references go commands. DEPENDENCIES: Low-effort fix. Independent of schema migration.; AUDIT-ARCH-3: Fan-in stability hotspots -- datom (41 importers), store (31), schema (17). Any API change to these modules cascades across the entire kernel. datom.rs defines EntityId, Attribute, Value, Datom, Op, TxId, ProvenanceType -- touched by every module. store.rs defines Store, Transaction, Frontier, TxData -- used by 31 modules. schema.rs defines ValueType, Cardinality, ResolutionMode -- used by 17 modules. SOLUTION: Freeze the public APIs of these three modules. Any changes should go through a deprecation cycle. Consider extracting datom.rs types into a dedicated braid-types leaf crate with zero dependencies, following the crate architecture algebra: leaf -> core -> facade -> binary. JUSTIFICATION: High fan-in modules are stability requirements -- changes cascade widely. Crate architecture algebra says leaf crates should be FREE objects (no imposed structure). VERIFICATION: Establish API surface tests (compile-time checks that public types and methods exist). DEPENDENCIES: datom.rs extraction is prerequisite for any crate structure changes.; MINOR-3: No ergonomics audit conducted — DOGFOOD-2 score 3.48/10 may reflect UX problems [GAP, from meta-analysis]. None of the four audit passes evaluated CLI usability, error message helpfulness, or developer experience. The DOGFOOD-2 score of 3.48/10 on an external Go project suggests problems that code-level auditing cannot capture: unclear error messages, confusing command hierarchy, insufficient onboarding, poor default behavior. SOLUTION: Conduct a targeted ergonomics audit: (1) Have a fresh agent run braid init + observe + harvest + seed cycle on an unfamiliar project. (2) Record every point of confusion, unhelpful error, or unexpected behavior. (3) Score each command on a 1-5 usability scale. VERIFICATION: Ergonomics audit document with actionable findings. Target: average command usability above 3.5/5. DEPENDENCIES: Should happen alongside META-3 (S0 validation) — same test but measuring different dimensions.; AUDIT-EXT POLICY-UNWIRED (from AUDIT_REPORT Section 2.3 + 5.1): PolicyConfig is well-designed but ignored by the rest of the kernel. PROBLEM: PolicyConfig (policy.rs) is SOUND — well-designed with BoundaryDef, AnomalyDef, CalibrationConfig, and WeightAdjustment types. But compute_fitness() in bilateral.rs ignores PolicyConfig weights and uses hardcoded constants (bilateral.rs:80-92). The policy manifest architecture exists but the rest of the kernel doesn't use it. This makes policy.rs architecturally correct but operationally dead for fitness computation. JUSTIFICATION: This is the paradox at the heart of C8: the solution exists (policy.rs) but the rest of the code bypasses it. compute_fitness_from_policy() exists in policy.rs but Store::fitness() falls back to MaterializedViews when no policy datoms are present — and since Layers 1-4 are hardcoded rather than transacted via policy, the fallback always activates. The policy system is a chicken-and-egg problem: it needs policy datoms to work, but policy datoms aren't transacted because the hardcoded path works. SOLUTION: This is the same fix as F-C8-001 (schema to policy manifests). Once braid init transacts policy datoms, compute_fitness_from_policy() becomes the primary path, and the hardcoded MaterializedViews fallback can be deprecated. VERIFICATION: After policy manifest adoption, grep 'W_VALIDATION\\|W_COVERAGE\\|W_DRIFT' bilateral.rs returns zero results (weights come from policy). DEPENDENCIES: Requires F-C8-001. This is the downstream benefit of moving schema to policy. FINDING SOURCE: AUDIT_REPORT.md Sections 2.3, 5.1. FILES: crates/braid-kernel/src/policy.rs, bilateral.rs. SEVERITY: High. WAVE: 2. EFFORT: Included in F-C8-001.; AUDIT-EXT ARCH-CIRCULAR (from AUDIT_REPORT): 4 circular dependency cycles found in kernel. PROBLEM: (1) store <-> merge (HIGH severity): store.rs imports merge::CascadeReceipt, merge.rs imports store::Store. Should extract shared types to types.rs. (2) store <-> bilateral inline (MEDIUM): bilateral functions called from store for fitness computation, store types used in bilateral. Extract FitnessScore/Components to fitness.rs. (3) routing <-> context (MEDIUM): both import from each other for context assembly. Merge into one module or extract shared types. (4) proptest_strategies <-> bilateral (LOW): test helper depends on bilateral types. Move arb_fitness_* into bilateral test module. JUSTIFICATION: Circular dependencies prevent independent compilation, make change impact analysis unreliable, and violate the dependency graph principle (leaf -> core -> facade -> binary). They indicate that module boundaries are drawn in the wrong place. SOLUTION: Extract shared types to neutral modules. The store-merge cycle is most critical because these are the algebraic core. VERIFICATION: No circular imports. cargo-depgraph shows DAG structure. DEPENDENCIES: Independent. Simplifies all future refactoring. FILES: store.rs, merge.rs, bilateral.rs, routing.rs, context.rs, proptest_strategies.rs. SEVERITY: Medium. WAVE: 1. EFFORT: 4h.; AUDIT-COH-3: 30 functions exceeding 50 lines lack any spec reference. The largest untraced functions: build_orientation() (515 lines, seed.rs) -- the largest function in the kernel with no INV/ADR/NEG traceability. compute_routing_from_store_inner() (260 lines, routing.rs) -- core work prioritization algorithm. synthesize_narrative() (256 lines, harvest.rs) -- harvest narrative generation. create_task_datoms() (249 lines, task.rs). emit_proptest() (213 lines, compiler.rs). format_verbose() (174 lines, bilateral.rs). compute_calibration_metrics() (165 lines, routing.rs). These functions contain significant logic that should trace to spec elements per C5 (traceability). SOLUTION: For each function, identify the invariant it preserves or the ADR it implements. Add spec reference comments. Where no spec element exists, create one (see AUDIT-COH-2). VERIFICATION: After adding references, grep for functions > 50 lines without INV/ADR/NEG should return 0. DEPENDENCIES: Related to AUDIT-COH-2 (some functions need new spec elements first).; AUDIT-TYPE-004: BraidError string-wrapping variants (Parse, DatalogParse, Validation, EmptyResult) lose caller-distinguishable structure. PROBLEM: crates/braid/src/error.rs:23-31 has 4 variants wrapping bare String. Callers cannot programmatically distinguish specific parse failures or validation errors. error_info() maps at variant level but loses detail. SOLUTION: Consider structured inner types for at least Validation (carry parameter name + constraint violated) and Parse (carry position + expected token). VERIFICATION: match arm on Validation can distinguish specific validation failures. DEPENDS-ON: None. INTERACTS-WITH: None (CLI crate only).; AUDIT-EXT SPEC-DEFECTS (from AUDIT_REPORT Section 4.5): 6 specification-implementation defects. (1) Genesis attr count drift: spec says 19 (INV-SCHEMA-002), implementation has 57. Falsification condition fails against current code. (2) Schema monotonicity via validate_evolution() exists but is not called in the transact path — dead code. (3) Retraction precondition not checked — can retract never-asserted datoms (INV-SCHEMA-004 L0 violated). (4) Harvest crystallization guard missing — NEG-HARVEST-003 (no premature crystallization) is unguarded. (5) Phi metric uses entity overlap not link-based traceability — spec defines D_IS via :spec/traces-to links but code uses entity set membership in ISP namespaces. (6) Test results not stored as datoms — the Impl-Behavior boundary (INV-BILATERAL-005) is completely unmonitored. JUSTIFICATION: Each of these is a spec-implementation divergence — exactly the kind of structural divergence the bilateral loop is designed to detect. That the bilateral loop didn't surface these (they were found by external audit) is itself a finding about bilateral scan effectiveness. SOLUTION: Fix each individually: (1) update spec or impl to match, (2) wire validate_evolution into transact, (3) add retraction precondition check, (4) implement crystallization guard, (5) switch Phi to link-based, (6) add test result datom recording. VERIFICATION: Each falsification condition in the referenced INV no longer fires. DEPENDENCIES: (5) interacts with F-C8-003 (trilateral configurability). (6) is a new feature. FILES: schema.rs, store.rs, harvest.rs, trilateral.rs. SEVERITY: Mixed (P1-P2). WAVE: 1-2. EFFORT: 12h total.; AUDIT-EXT STRATEGIC-RISKS (from PROJECT_ASSESSMENT Section 7): 5 strategic risks to production readiness. Risk 1: F(S) may have a structural ceiling below 1.0 — the 7 components may be anti-correlated by construction (improving V requires adding tests which increases denominator for C and I). Mitigation: verification sprint will empirically test this. Risk 2: Single-customer overfitting — 46 sessions of DDIS-on-DDIS have optimized the system for one domain. DOGFOOD-2 3.48/10 on Go CLI may indicate universal substrate has quietly become DDIS substrate. Mitigation: S0-CLOSE external validation. Risk 3: Complexity acceleration without consolidation — 127K LOC in 46 sessions = 2,766 LOC/session, growing faster than verified (265 untested INVs), documented (142 gaps), or self-tracked (hypothesis degrading). Mitigation: verification sprint + module decomposition. Risk 4: Daemon may be a distraction — validate S0 with CLI first, only build daemon if CLI validates core hypothesis. Risk 5: Formalism may be too expensive — 22 spec files, 83+ INVs, 30+ ADRs, hypothesis ledger, bilateral scans, fitness functions, 8-type taxonomy. If F(S) moves after verification sprint, formalism earns its keep. If not, lighter formalism may be more appropriate. JUSTIFICATION: These are existential risks, not code bugs. They question whether the project's approach works, not whether the code is correct. The verification sprint (Priority 2) is the diagnostic for risks 1, 3, and 5. S0-CLOSE (Priority 4) is the diagnostic for risks 2 and 4. DEPENDENCIES: All depend on completing Wave 0-1 fixes first. FINDING SOURCE: PROJECT_ASSESSMENT.md Section 7.; HYGIENE-1: ~20 production unwrap() calls lack SAFETY comments [MEDIUM, from FULL_AUDIT F-ERR-001]. 1180 unwrap calls total (719 kernel, 461 CLI), ~90% in test code. ~20 in kernel production code, ~15 in CLI production code without proof comments. Most concerning: query/graph.rs:60-61 get_mut(src).unwrap() in add_edge (panics if node not pre-added), seed.rs:3084,3121 kept.pop().unwrap() (panics on empty vec). SOLUTION: (1) Add // SAFETY: comments to all justified production unwraps. (2) Replace ~5 genuinely risky unwraps with proper error returns. (3) Enable clippy::unwrap_used for non-test code. VERIFICATION: cargo clippy with unwrap_used lint shows zero violations in non-test code. DEPENDENCIES: Independent. ~4 hours.; SPEC-GAP-4: Tests test implementation behavior, not specification invariants — systematic coverage gap [MEDIUM, from FULL_AUDIT F-TEST-001]. 2043 tests exist, but no formal mapping from tests to specification invariants. Most tests verify behavior (does transact add a datom?) rather than invariants (is INV-STORE-001 satisfied for all reachable states?). Some tests DO reference invariants: proptest_store_append_only tests INV-STORE-001, kani_merge_commutative tests INV-STORE-004. But most dont: test_create_task tests task creation works without referencing any INV, test_query_entity tests query returns results without referencing INV-QUERY-002. SOLUTION: (1) Add doc = Witnesses: INV-STORE-001 attributes to tests that witness invariants. (2) Generate coverage matrix via braid trace --source tests/. (3) Target: every Stage 0 INV has at least one test with explicit witness reference. VERIFICATION: braid witness completeness shows above 80% for Stage 0. DEPENDENCIES: Related to AUDIT-COH-1 (untested namespaces) and AUDIT-VERIFY-1 (verification roadmap). ~16 hours incremental.; AUDIT-SOUND-9: Schema validate_evolution() is dead code -- never called from transact path [LOW]. schema.rs:540 defines validate_evolution() that correctly detects: attribute removal (line 546), value type changes (549-553), cardinality narrowing Many-to-One (556-559). But this function has ZERO callers in the transact/coherence path. Store::transact() rebuilds schema from datoms after each schema-modifying transaction (store.rs:1432-1435) without validating evolution. Schema changes could introduce contradictions with existing data. Also: Kani has no schema retraction safety harness. SOLUTION: Call validate_evolution(old_schema, new_schema) in Store::transact() when schema_changed flag is true, before rebuilding. Add Kani harness proving meta-schema retraction has no effect. VERIFICATION: Unit test: assert cardinality narrowing Many-to-One with existing multi-valued data produces error. Kani: prove retract of :db/valueType datom does not remove attribute from schema. DEPENDENCIES: Related to AUDIT-SOUND-1 (coherence gate wiring) but independent.; OPEN-LOOP-6: Bilateral CC-3 permanently defaults true — phantom coherence check [from AUDIT_REPORT]. In bilateral.rs, coherence condition CC-3 always evaluates to true (default). This means one of the coherence conditions contributing to F(S) drift component is a no-op — it never detects any divergence. The condition was likely a placeholder that was never implemented. Having a phantom check inflates the coherence score by providing false assurance. SOLUTION: Either implement CC-3 with its intended semantics (check what it was supposed to detect) or remove it and adjust the coherence score to use only the conditions that actually work. VERIFICATION: After