ontext enum has Rust-specific variants: UnitTest, PropTest, KaniProof, Stateright. Lines 189-213 detect proptest!, kani::proof, test attributes. A compliance team has no source code; a research lab has experiments not test functions. SOLUTION: Make trace scanner an extractor registered through policy. Rust scanner is one extractor; Go scanner, Python scanner, manual evidence scanner are others. Kernel provides depth classification schema; extractors populate it. Note: comment_prefixes_for_extension() at lines 43-69 already supports polyglot scanning, showing C8 awareness -- only depth classification needs extraction. VERIFICATION: Register Go-specific extractor, verify trace scan works with Go test patterns. DEPENDENCIES: Independent of other C8 violations. Lower risk than schema migration.; META-6: Formalism overhead may exceed value for single developer [STRATEGIC RISK, from PROJECT_ASSESSMENT Risk 5]. The project carries: 22 spec files, 83+ invariants, 30+ ADRs, 265 verification tasks, hypothesis ledger, bilateral scans, fitness functions, 8-type divergence taxonomy. Each internally consistent and well-motivated. But aggregate cost of maintaining formalism may exceed value — especially as solo-developer-with-AI-agents project. ASSESSMENT: This is a risk to MONITOR not eliminate. If S0 validates and external users adopt, formalism pays for itself through reduced divergence. If project remains solo, lighter-weight formalism may be appropriate. The saw-tooth model is the diagnostic: if F(S) moves after verification sprint, formalism is earning its keep. If not, reconsider. SOLUTION: No immediate action. Track ratio of time-on-formalism vs time-on-implementation across next 5 sessions. If formalism consumes more than 30% of session time without F(S) improvement, simplify. DEPENDENCIES: Outcome depends on META-2 (verification sprint) and META-3 (S0 validation).; OPEN-LOOP-2: Compiler-generated proptests never executed [from FULL_AUDIT loop analysis + AUDIT_REPORT]. compiler.rs (3072 LOC) detects patterns in the store and generates proptest code via emit_proptest(). But no pipeline executes the generated tests. The output is produced but never consumed — a textbook open loop (NEG-010). SOLUTION: Add CI step that runs braid compile --proptest, writes generated test file to a temp location, then runs cargo test on it. Alternatively, integrate generated tests into the standard test suite via a build script. VERIFICATION: Generated proptest produces at least 1 test. Running that test exercises at least 1 store property. DEPENDENCIES: Independent. ~4 hours.; AUDIT-SPEC-005: Store::merge() mutates target in-place, exposing intermediate inconsistent state. PROBLEM: store.rs:1471 merge(&mut self, other: &Store) mutates the target during merge — indexes are cleared then rebuilt (lines 1504-1508). Between clearing and rebuild, any concurrent read would see inconsistent state. Spec defines MERGE: Store x Store -> Store as pure function. SOLUTION: Low priority at Stage 0 (single-threaded). When concurrent access needed (Stage 3+), implement ArcSwap MVCC so merge produces a new Store atomically. For now, document that merge is NOT safe for concurrent access. VERIFICATION: Doc comment on merge() states single-threaded requirement. DEPENDS-ON: None. INTERACTS-WITH: Stage 3 multi-agent coordination.; AUDIT-SOUND-3: Hypothesis ledger dimensional mismatch causes structurally degrading calibration [HIGH]. Predicted values recorded at harvest (routing.rs:1198): predicted=routing.impact.clamp(0.0,1.0) -- an R(t) importance score in [0,1]. Actual outcomes at task close (task.rs:1176): actual_delta=fitness.total-pre_close_fitness -- raw F(S) change (typically near 0 for individual task closes). These have different dimensions. Prediction 0.8 with actual_delta 0.01 produces error 0.79. Mean error converges toward ~0.5 structurally. Current state: error=0.521, trend=degrading -- expected and permanent. SOLUTION: Change prediction to estimated delta-F(S) using project_delta() (exists in bilateral.rs). Makes both quantities commensurable. Also add calibration epoch mechanism: :calibration/epoch datom marking methodology change, so pre-epoch hypotheses excluded from metrics. JUSTIFICATION: Calibration requires comparing like with like. Acquisition function alpha=E[delta-F(S)]/cost requires delta-F(S) predictions, not importance scores. VERIFICATION: After fix, record 20+ hypotheses, verify mean error trends downward. E2E test: create task with known coverage impact, close it, verify prediction within 0.1 of actual. DEPENDENCIES: Depends on AUDIT-SOUND-2 (F(S) semantics). Blocks AUDIT-LOOP-1 (calibration closure).; AUDIT-EXT HIGH-1 (from AUDIT_REPORT + PROJECT_ASSESSMENT): Hypothesis ledger dimensional mismatch — predicted R(t) scores vs actual delta-F(S) are different units. PROBLEM: The hypothesis ledger records predicted values as normalized R(t) importance scores in [0,1]. Actual values are raw F(S) deltas (typically near 0 for individual task closes). Mean error converges toward ~0.5 because the quantities being compared have different dimensions. The degrading trend (error 0.521) is structural, not a calibration failure — the acquisition function compares apples to oranges. PROJECT_ASSESSMENT confirms: mean error was 0.254 in Session 036 (24 manually completed hypotheses), then degraded to 0.521 as subsequent sessions added predictions without matching outcomes. JUSTIFICATION: This is not a tuning problem — it is a design error. Calibration requires predicted and actual to be in the same units. R(t) scores measure task importance; delta-F(S) measures fitness change. These are fundamentally different quantities. No amount of calibration will make them converge because they measure different things. SOLUTION: Either (1) change predicted values to estimated delta-F(S) (the acquisition function should predict how much F(S) will change when a task is completed), or (2) normalize both to the same scale. Option 1 is more principled. Also wire automatic outcome detection in braid close (see AUDIT-EXT-CALIBRATION). VERIFICATION: After fix, mean error should decrease over 10 completed hypotheses. Predicted and actual should have same units. DEPENDENCIES: Interacts with AUDIT-EXT-CALIBRATION (automatic outcome detection). Both are needed for the calibration loop to close. Also relates to F-INV-002 (F(S) monotonicity). FINDING SOURCE: AUDIT_REPORT.md Section 2.2 HIGH-1, PROJECT_ASSESSMENT.md Section 4. FILES: crates/braid-kernel/src/routing.rs (hypothesis recording), crates/braid/src/commands/task.rs (outcome matching). SEVERITY: High. WAVE: 1. EFFORT: 8h.; AUDIT-LOOP-001: Exploration entity confidence never updated after outcome — open calibration loop. PROBLEM: Schema layer 3 defines :exploration/confidence (Double). Concept crystallization reads it. But no mechanism UPDATEs exploration confidence based on whether the exploration led to a useful outcome (promoted to spec, abandoned, merged into concept). The observation-projection duality requires a feedback loop from projection outcome back to observation quality. SOLUTION: When an exploration entity is promoted (via promote.rs), update its confidence to 1.0. When abandoned, update to 0.0. When merged into a concept, update based on concept quality. This closes the calibration loop for observations. VERIFICATION: proptest: after promotion, exploration confidence = 1.0. After abandonment, confidence = 0.0. DEPENDS-ON: None. INTERACTS-WITH: W2-008 (guidance uses exploration confidence).; AUDIT-C8-3: MaterializedViews ISP namespace classification hardcoded [HARD C8 violation, Priority 3]. store.rs:642-764 observe_datom() classifies attributes into Intent/Spec/Impl by matching prefixes: :exploration/, :session/, :harvest/ = Intent; :spec/, :element/ = Spec; :impl/, :task/ = Impl. This ISP trilateral model is core DDIS framework. SOLUTION: Classification should read from policy boundary source/target patterns via :policy/boundary-source and :policy/boundary-target datoms. The policy system already supports these patterns. VERIFICATION: After fix, configure custom namespace boundaries in policy, verify MaterializedViews classifies correctly. Verify existing ISP classification still works with DDIS policy manifest. DEPENDENCIES: Depends on AUDIT-C8-1 (schema L1+L2 must move to policy first). Interacts with AUDIT-C8-7 (boundary enum).; AUDIT-COH-4: Three parallel F(S) computation paths produce different values for identical store state. (1) Batch path (bilateral.rs:869 compute_fitness): rescans store datoms, uses full methodology M(t) score. (2) Views path (store.rs:770-890 views.fitness()): uses incremental accumulators, different H (harvest quality) heuristic based on observation density. (3) Policy path (bilateral.rs:729 compute_fitness_from_policy): reads policy boundary weights, maps boundaries to 7-component struct by positional index (fragile). Store::fitness() at store.rs:1650 tries policy path first, falls back to views. The policy path has one SpecImplBoundary registered by default; boundaries[1..6] get vacuous 1.0 scores, producing inflated totals. SOLUTION: Unify into a single canonical path. Use MaterializedViews accumulators as the single computation source (they are maintained incrementally and are always current). Eliminate the batch rescan path. The policy path should read FROM views, not scan independently. VERIFICATION: After unification, compute F(S) via the single path; compare to both old paths on a test store, verify the canonical path agrees with batch (the most correct one). DEPENDENCIES: Interacts with AUDIT-SOUND-2 (F(S) monotonicity) and AUDIT-PERF-1 (scan elimination). Unifying paths eliminates both the disagreement and the performance overhead.; AUDIT-EXT PERF-MEMORY (from AUDIT_REPORT): Datom cloned 5-7x into indexes — estimated 100-250MB for 108K datoms. PROBLEM: Each datom is stored in the primary BTreeSet AND cloned into entity_index, attribute_index, vaet_index, avet_index, and potentially live_view. With 108K datoms, each containing String-based Attribute and Value, the memory footprint is estimated at 100-250MB. With index-by-offset (storing references or indices instead of clones), this drops to ~25-55MB — a 4-5x reduction. JUSTIFICATION: At 108K datoms this is tolerable. At 1M datoms, the 1-2.5GB memory footprint becomes the scaling bottleneck. The fundamental issue: Datom contains owned Strings (Attribute, Value::String, Value::Keyword) that are cloned on every index insertion. Attribute interning (~200 unique attributes cloned 108K times) would eliminate most of the duplication. SOLUTION: (1) Intern Attribute values — use Arc<str> or a string interner so all datoms with the same attribute share one allocation. (2) Store datom indices (or Arc<Datom>) in secondary indexes instead of clones. (3) These are performance optimizations, not correctness fixes — defer until scale requires it. VERIFICATION: Memory profiling shows <50MB for 108K datoms after interning. DEPENDENCIES: Independent performance optimization. No correctness impact. FILES: crates/braid-kernel/src/store.rs (index insertion), datom.rs (Attribute type). SEVERITY: Medium. WAVE: 4. EFFORT: 12h.; AUDIT-SOUND-5: NaN in Value::Double can enter store unguarded [MEDIUM]. Value::Double(OrderedFloat(f64::NAN)) passes schema validation (schema.rs:515-530 only checks type match). OrderedFloat provides total order so BTreeSet works, but serde_json serializes NaN as null, causing content_hash() divergence across platforms. Proptest explicitly filters NaN (proptest_strategies.rs:96: prop_filter finite floats only). No Kani proof tests NaN. SOLUTION: Add NaN/Inf rejection in schema validation: validate_datom should reject Value::Double where inner is NaN or Inf. Alternatively, add proptest coverage for NaN behavior. VERIFICATION: Unit test: assert transact with Value::Double(NaN) returns error. Proptest: remove the NaN filter, verify CRDT properties still hold (they should due to OrderedFloat). DEPENDENCIES: Independent. Low interaction with other findings.; CORR-6: FitnessDelta and FitnessComponents use f64 without NaN guards — 3 unwrap panics [MEDIUM, from FULL_AUDIT F-TYPE-004]. FitnessScore(f64) and FitnessComponents use raw f64 values. Three downstream consumers call .partial_cmp().unwrap() — bilateral.rs:326, bilateral.rs:408, bilateral.rs:587 in CLI. If any component computes as NaN (e.g. 0/0 from empty store with spec_count=0), the unwrap panics. Other call sites correctly use unwrap_or(Ordering::Equal). SOLUTION: Either (A) Replace FitnessScore(f64) with FitnessScore(OrderedFloat f64) — already a dependency, or (B) Add .unwrap_or(Ordering::Equal) to the 3 unguarded sites. Option A is cleaner. VERIFICATION: FitnessScore(f64::NAN).partial_cmp() does not panic. DEPENDENCIES: Independent. ~1 hour. Related to AUDIT-SOUND-5 (NaN in Value::Double) but different type.; AUDIT-TYPE-3: ~10 stringly-typed kernel APIs where newtypes would eliminate invalid states. Most impactful: classify_command(command: &str) matches ~20 string literals -- should be a Command enum (compile error if new command not handled). count_signals(store, signal_type: &str) matches :signal.type/* patterns -- should be SignalType enum. find_task_by_id(store, task_id: &str) takes freeform string -- should be TaskId newtype. get_config/set_config_datoms take raw &str keys -- should be ConfigKey newtype. create_branch(name: &str, purpose: &str) -- should be BranchName newtype. Also: one boolean blindness instance: run_cycle(store, history, with_spectral: bool) -- should be CycleMode::Full|CycleMode::Fast enum. JUSTIFICATION: rust-formal-engineering Rule 4 -- newtype every domain boundary. Single validation point at construction; all downstream code receives proven-valid value. VERIFICATION: After introducing newtypes, verify cargo check catches any callers passing raw strings. DEPENDENCIES: Independent. Can be done incrementally.; AUDIT-ARCH-003: Seed module's upward dependency on task module violates kernel layering. PROBLEM: seed.rs imports crate::task::{all_tasks, task_summary} creating a dependency from a core lifecycle module (seed) to a domain-specific module (task). Tasks are a DDIS concept — not all domains have tasks. SOLUTION: Seed should assemble context from generic store queries (entities matching policy-defined categories), not from task-specific functions. Move task-specific seed integration to the CLI seed command, which knows about DDIS concepts. VERIFICATION: seed.rs has no import from crate::task. DEPENDS-ON: W1-003 (policy defines entity categories). INTERACTS-WITH: W3-001 (all_tasks deduplication).; AUDIT-PERF-1: Approximately 20 full O(N) datom scans in single braid status call. At 108K datoms = ~2.16M iterations. Specific locations: bilateral.rs:833 entities_matching_pattern called 7x (once per boundary) -- should use attribute_index namespace-prefix lookup. bilateral.rs:1170 compute_contradiction_complement full scan -- MaterializedViews should track this. trilateral.rs:394 compute_beta_1 full scan for entity graph -- VAET index has Ref datoms. task.rs:979 all_tasks called 2x in status path -- should use attribute_datoms(:task/id). methodology.rs:433,515,535,768 four telemetry scans -- all should use attribute_index. Also: MaterializedViews accumulators already contain most needed data but the policy-driven F(S) path (compute_fitness_from_policy) does not use them. SOLUTION: Replace each full scan with corresponding index lookup. Use MaterializedViews accumulators as primary F(S) computation path, eliminating the parallel policy-path full scans. VERIFICATION: Benchmark braid status before/after. At 108K datoms, target: 4s to under 1s. At 1M datoms (projected in 20 sessions), should remain under 2s. DEPENDENCIES: Interacts with AUDIT-PERF-2 (merge rebuild) and AUDIT-SOUND-2 (F(S) 3-path disagreement -- unifying paths eliminates scans).; AUDIT-EXT DOGFOOD (from PROJECT_ASSESSMENT Section 5): DOGFOOD-2 scored